# Research Assistant Formatting Guidelines

This document serves as the definitive guide for all formatting and style rules in the research project. All content must strictly follow these guidelines to maintain consistency and academic standards.

## Purpose
These rules ensure:
1. Consistent document formatting across all project files
2. Professional academic writing standards
3. Proper citation and reference management
4. Clear and standardized visual elements (figures, tables)
5. Quality control in academic documentation

## Document Structure
1. Use consistent heading hierarchy:
   ```markdown
   # Main Title (Title Case)

   ## Abstract

   ## Introduction
   ### Background
   ### Research Questions

   ## Methods
   ### Study Design
   ### Data Collection

   ## Results
   ### Key Findings
   ### Statistical Analysis

   ## Discussion
   ### Interpretation
   ### Limitations

   ## Conclusion
   ### Summary
   ### Future Directions

   ## References
   ```

## Citation Standards
1. Use IEEE format for in-text citations and references:
   ```markdown
   In-text: [1], [2], [1], [3]
   Multiple: [1], [2], [3]
   Range: [1]-[4]
   ```

2. Reference format:
   ```markdown
   [1] A. Author, B. Author, "Title of paper," Journal Name, vol. 1, no. 2, pp. 123-456, 2023.
   ```

3. Include DOI or permanent links:
   ```markdown
   DOI: 10.1234/journal.2023.1234
   arXiv: arXiv:2301.12345
   ```

## Image Formatting
1. Center all images using div syntax:
   ```markdown
   <div style="width: 500px; margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;">

   <img src="sources_png/paper_id/page_001.png" alt=" "/>

   </div>

   ##### *Figure N: Descriptive Title - Illustrates key components or findings. Adapted from Author et al. (YEAR), Fig. X.*
   ```

2. Image specifications:
   - Width: 500px for all figures
   - Format: PNG preferred
   - Resolution: minimum 300 DPI
   - Empty alt text to prevent export issues

3. Figure caption format:
   - Use H5 (#####) for consistent styling
   - Include figure number, title, and source
   - Italicize using asterisks

## Table Formatting
1. Standard table format:
   ```markdown
   **Table N: Descriptive Title**

   | Header 1 | Header 2 | Header 3 |
   |----------|----------|----------|
   | Data     | Data     | Data     |

   *Note: Description of the table. Adapted from Author et al. (YEAR), Table X.*
   ```

2. Multi-source tables:
   ```markdown
   *Note: Framework synthesized from multiple sources: Author1 et al. (YEAR1), Author2 et al. (YEAR2), Author3 (YEAR3).*
   ```

## Academic Writing Style
1. Use formal, objective language
2. Write in third person
3. Use active voice where appropriate
4. Maintain consistent terminology
5. Define abbreviations at first use

## Source Integration
1. Direct quotes:
   ```markdown
   Author states that "exact quote" [1].
   ```

2. Paraphrasing:
   ```markdown
   Studies have shown significant improvements in outcomes [1], [2].
   ```

3. Synthesis:
   ```markdown
   Multiple studies [1]-[3] demonstrate consistent patterns in...
   ```

## Quality Control
1. Verify all citations match references
2. Check image/table numbering sequence
3. Ensure consistent formatting throughout
4. Validate all DOIs and links
5. Review abbreviation consistency
